         <div type="commentary" subtype="linebyline">
            <list>
               <item corresp="#lb1" xml:space="preserve">
            <ref>1</ref>
            <p>
              The integration [ὑπ]ν̣ωτικόν (Andorlini, see
              <ref target="http://papyri.info/dclp/63118">P.Oxy. VIII 1088</ref>
              .66) would be very tempting, especially in view of the inclusion of poppy seed in the recipe, but the extant traces and the available space seem to guarantee [ἀρ]α̣ιωτικόν. The application of this recipe to the forehead, and its use of poppy seed, might suggest that its purpose was to relieve some sort of perceived blockage or congestion in the head, perhaps associated with pain.
            </p>
          </item>
               <item corresp="#lb2" xml:space="preserve">
            <ref>2-3</ref>
            <p>
              The 'dispersing' (διαφορητική) property of mouse droppings (see Orib.
              <emph rend="italics">Coll.</emph>
              XIV 62.1) was considered active in the relief of certain kinds of pain in the head (see Gal.
              <emph rend="italics">Comp.med.loc.</emph>
              XII 548-9 K.), and it may be related to the rarefying action referred to in the recipe title.
            </p>
          </item>
               <item corresp="#lb4" xml:space="preserve">
            <ref>4</ref>
            <p>
              Perfumed oil in this recipe would presumably counteract the unwelcome odour of the mouse droppings, but such unguents were commonly used as mixing agents for the preparation of ointments and plasters. When applied to the head in the form of an ointment, as here, perfumed oils were widely considered effective for headaches (see e.g. Dsc.
              <emph rend="italics">MM</emph>
              I 43.4).
            </p>
          </item>
               <item corresp="#lb5" xml:space="preserve">
            <ref>5</ref>
            <p>
              For [διά]χρειε, much rarer than [ἐπί]χριε, see Orib.
              <emph rend="italics">Syn.</emph>
              VIII 17.6.
            </p>
          </item>
               <item corresp="#lb8" xml:space="preserve">
            <ref>8-13</ref>
            <p>
              We may note that the four ingredients found here are also those used in the preparation of oxymel as described at Dsc.
              <emph rend="italics">MM</emph>
              V 14. This is clearly a purgative of the most basic kind.
            </p>
          </item>
               <item corresp="#lb12" xml:space="preserve">
            <ref>12</ref>
            <p>
              The verb κιρνάω in medical literature is used of mixing or tempering liquids (e.g. Dsc. III 22.4; Orib.
              <emph rend="italics">Coll.</emph>
              V 30.36, 38). The sense required here is of dividing or portioning out the liquid in certain amounts ("by the
              <emph rend="italics">kyathos</emph>
              ") once it has been mixed, but no parallels for such a usage of κιρνάω survive.
            </p>
          </item>
            </list>
